<div id="review_98028750" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/98028750" />
    <a title="Beth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1018754-beth"><img alt="Beth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227715451p2/1018754.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/98028750?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beth" href="/user/show/1018754-beth">Beth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer98028750" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3897725097017804677">This is an idea book, not a character book. In this book, Card is exploring the idea that a group of people would deliberately go back in time to alter events in such a way that human history would work out &quot;better.&quot; The height of hubris, definitely, for any group of mortals to think they could predict future events accurately enough to know what to &quot;improve.&quot; I think that Card is right that humanity would have to be in the brink of extinction before they would permit such an experiment.<br/><br/>There ar</span>
  <span id="freeText3897725097017804677" style="display:none">This is an idea book, not a character book. In this book, Card is exploring the idea that a group of people would deliberately go back in time to alter events in such a way that human history would work out "better." The height of hubris, definitely, for any group of mortals to think they could predict future events accurately enough to know what to "improve." I think that Card is right that humanity would have to be in the brink of extinction before they would permit such an experiment.<br /><br />There are lots of ideas in this book...global warming, geopolitics, time travel, the complicated and interrelated history of European and ancient American peoples....it's also an exploration of the life of Christopher Columbus, which is very interesting. Columbus himself is the only fully fleshed-out character in the novel. The rest of the characters exist solely as props to keep the plot moving...they have just enough detail to add a little bit of human interest to the very complicated story.<br /><br />I thought the book was fascinating. But don't read it if you have to have a character you love in order to really enjoy a novel. You won't find that here. <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="3897725097017804677" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


