    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3291212651" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3291212651" />
    <a title="Aberdeen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64266205-aberdeen"><img alt="Aberdeen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485372539p2/64266205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3291212651?book_show_action=true">Apr 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aberdeen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aberdeen" href="/user/show/64266205-aberdeen">Aberdeen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64266205-aberdeen?shelf=fantasy-in-our-world">fantasy-in-our-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64266205-aberdeen?shelf=4-stars">4-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64266205-aberdeen?shelf=not-just-white-people">not-just-white-people</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64266205-aberdeen?shelf=blow-my-mind">blow-my-mind</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/64266205-aberdeen?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3291212651" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11795662386214193087"><b>A lot of my thoughts on this are spoilery, but here’s the tl;dr version: I loved this book. Its driving force is ideas, which is right up my alley. It was the perfect blend of being grounded in historical detail but full of idealism and hypotheticals (what science fiction is for). It had a fascinating world-building (both historical and in the far future), characters I cared about, and ethical dilemmas.</b> Now for more in-depth thoughts and critiques of other people’s critiques … <br/><br/>Another reviewer s</span>
  <span id="freeText11795662386214193087" style="display:none"><b>A lot of my thoughts on this are spoilery, but here’s the tl;dr version: I loved this book. Its driving force is ideas, which is right up my alley. It was the perfect blend of being grounded in historical detail but full of idealism and hypotheticals (what science fiction is for). It had a fascinating world-building (both historical and in the far future), characters I cared about, and ethical dilemmas.</b> Now for more in-depth thoughts and critiques of other people’s critiques … <br /><br />Another reviewer said this is an ideas book rather than a character book. I agree that the ideas are the main propellers (which is personally right up my alley, although I completely understand that it isn't for everyone) but the characters also felt very real and sympathetic to me. Card did an admirable job making each of them unique and fleshed-out despite relatively small screen time (due to the multi-generational nature of the story, as well as the emphasis on ideas) <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[(example: that scene with Diko and Hunahpu at the very end? It gave me an ache in my chest, which shows me that I really cared about them.)  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. <br /><br />Because the ideas are the main point, the ending wasn't as overdone as it otherwise would have felt. In a pure novel, it would have felt preachy <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[or too perfect. This may be a weird comparison, but it reminds me of the end of Jane Austen's Northanger Abbey, which I didn't like because it was too obvious and perfect <i>for a novel<i>, for the kind of book it is.</i></i> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> It is the culmination of the idea, a thought experiment. <b>This whole book is a thought experiment,</b> and a lot of the negative reviews I read stemmed from the fact that people either didn't understand or like that. It’s fine if you don't enjoy that kind of book, but don't complain that it isn't historically accurate (duh—it’s a what-might-have-been) or an info dump (it’s science fiction!). <br /><br />I <i>love</i> all the ethical dilemmas this book made me wrestle with <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[question for those who read it: would it have been right to go back if humanity had actually been living in a paradise, if they hadn't found out that it was all doomed anyway? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. I love the interesting take on time travel and the fact that I could actually understand it. I love how it exposed me to cultures and a time period (central America and the Caribbean during the time of Columbus) that I know next to nothing about. Card’s list of resources at the end is impressive, how he did a lot of research to write this science fiction book (again! It's science-fiction! It's <i>not</i> historical fiction. It's just supposed to be grounded <i>enough</i> in what happened to provide a possible basis for another outcome). <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Also, I liked the ending. It was far more hopeful and positive than I expected. It didn't doom humanity again, and it didn't make Columbus the ultimate villain. It truly was his redemption. I'm sure this makes it very not-PC and will ruffle people’s feathers, but then, Card’s argument is also that the Mesoamerican people could've been formidable foes and that colonization was the greatest mistake of history, so it's not like he was being a white supremacist like some people claim. Of course, I am white, so I'd appreciate what from Central America or the Caribbean thinks about the story. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Last thing: I'm a Christian. Of course I don't agree with the way Christianity has often been used historically, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[nor do I agree with the new doctrines that the time travelers introduce  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. <b>But I appreciate that Card highlighted the importance that religion plays in creating societies, unifying (and dividing) cultures, and inspiring people unlike anything else can.</b> It's something our modern culture often overlooks. And Christianity really is the best source for hope and healing (although it looks rather the opposite of how it's used in this book: not as a political pawn but as a transformation of individuals). <br /><br />Fascinating, too, the thought that the Central Americans were more Christian than the Europeans. I absolutely agree that they acted far more Christian than many Europeans (Card did a good job balancing that view with a condom nation of human sacrifice). My only caveat to that is that true Christianity is about far more than our actions—you can act like a good person and still be far from a relationship with God.<br /><br />All that to say, this book really made me think, for which I love it.<br /><br />Also Card's writing style really reminds me of Brandon Sanderson's, which is quite an endorsement.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11795662386214193087" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


