    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2167747229" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2167747229" />
    <a title="Ellen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3166143-ellen"><img alt="Ellen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1470073908p2/3166143.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2167747229?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ellen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ellen" href="/user/show/3166143-ellen">Ellen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2167747229" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17908864715777374588">Outside of Ender&apos;s Game I&apos;m not a big fan of Scott Card&apos;s work -- the few I&apos;ve tried to read have put me to sleep. So, on that front this is a rousing success. Essentially a book about time travel, humans in the future have the ability to look back on all of human history, and realize that they can go back and reshape that history to undo all manner of evil. I don&apos;t think Scott Card fully understands how this world works, though; the explanation of how Pastwatch functions isn&apos;t real clear, and w</span>
  <span id="freeText17908864715777374588" style="display:none">Outside of Ender's Game I'm not a big fan of Scott Card's work -- the few I've tried to read have put me to sleep. So, on that front this is a rousing success. Essentially a book about time travel, humans in the future have the ability to look back on all of human history, and realize that they can go back and reshape that history to undo all manner of evil. I don't think Scott Card fully understands how this world works, though; the explanation of how Pastwatch functions isn't real clear, and when it comes to sending people back in time FOR THE FIRST TIME IN THIS HISTORY, they are inexplicably fully equipped to do this, understand perfectly how it will work...despite never having done it before. The characters aren't fully drawn and every woman and man who work together fall in love and get married, or at least get married. Scott Card has some pretty horrific beliefs, and so it would not surprise me if he ascribes to the Pence rule of never meeting with a woman alone; this book, anyway, doesn't suggest it's possible for a man to work alongside a woman without romance ensuing. <br /><br />In any case, it's sort of a fun look at reshaping history that takes forever to get to its point, and we spend far longer wandering around after Christopher Columbus than I'd like. I'm never quite clear on why everyone is so convinced of him as the man with the power to be the vessel through which they reshape history. Converting the world to Christianity is key to Scott Card's better version of the world, and sometimes his vision of the world really comes through in astounding ways. One of the Pastwatchers, Hunahpu, is a a Mayan descendent and at one point says: "I can promise you that a world ruled by the Tlaxcalans or the Mexica -- or even the Maya, for that matter -- would never have given rise to the democratic and tolerant and scientific values that eventually emerged from European culture..." (191-192). Good lecture, Orson Scott Card. Read this for book club and doubt I would have bothered otherwise, but it was more readable than most of his work outside Ender's Game.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17908864715777374588" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


